    # ========== PHASE 1 — THE DOORWAY (again) ==========

    "The vigil ended at oh-one-twenty."

    "Aeron did not stay for the last of it. He stayed for the naming and he stayed for the silence that came after the naming and he stayed for the moment Selene put her hand on his shoulder and left hers there for exactly the length of breath she wanted him to take. Then he stood up and walked out of the vigil room because the vigil room had decided what it needed to do and had done it, and the shape of the correct grief after a vigil is not more vigil."

    "He walked the south corridor."

    "He did not decide to come to the medbay. He walked the south corridor and the medbay wing branch was the one his feet chose when the corridor branched, and he noticed the choice after he had made it and did not argue with the choice."

    athought "Davel Ostra."

    athought "Davel Ostra."

    athought "Davel Ostra."

    athought "That is the rule. I am doing the rule in the corridor because the corridor is where I am. I am going to do the rule again in front of the board because the board is where the rule gets completed, and the rule in front of the board is not a performance — it is the place I am going tonight because the place I am going tonight is wherever the rule lives."

    "He reaches the main medical area door."

    "He stops in the doorway."

    "He does not enter."

    # ========== PHASE 2 — THE CAPPING ==========

    "Tessa is at the board."

    "Back to the door. The same clip lamp burning above the dead column. The marker in her right hand. She is not mid-letter. She is at the end of a letter. She is at the end of the last letter of the last name the day has given her, and the letter is the A at the end of OSTRA, and she is holding the marker tip a half-inch from the whiteboard the way she holds the punctuation-pause after the final letter of every name she writes."

    "She caps the marker."

    "Small plastic click."

    "The click is the scene's first sentence."

    "It reaches him in the doorway and it is the sentence that tells him what time this is inside the night. The night has a time and the time is: after."

    "She does not turn. She sets the marker on the shelf below the bottom edge of the board. Her hand stays on the shelf for a second longer than setting a marker down requires. Then it comes back to her side and she breathes."

    "He watches her breathe."

    "Then she speaks without turning."

    t "You can come in, Aeron."

    "It is the same sentence she gave him in s06 and it is not the same sentence. The sentence in s06 was an invitation into a ritual. The sentence tonight is an invitation into a room that is no longer doing ritual."

    "He comes in."

    # ========== PHASE 3 — THE BOARD TONIGHT ==========

    "He crosses the floor to the same place he stood in s06 — two steps behind her, angled so that the board is in both of their lines of sight. The board has had thirteen days of work since s06. Four new names on the dead column, not counting Davel. Seven names transferred up to the living column from the unassigned row because Tessa confirmed their stabilization on her shift rotations. One name moved the other direction — a fighter Tessa had put on the living column at dawn and had to move to the dead column at dusk. She did not say anything about the move when she made it. She just moved it. The board carries the move without commentary."

    "DAVEL OSTRA is the bottom entry on the dead column."

    "The ink is still wet-looking."

    athought "Davel Ostra."

    "Aeron says the name in his head for the fourth time tonight. The rule is a rule and he does the rule. Tessa's lips do not move. She is not saying Davel in her head right now because she said Davel in her head while she was writing Davel and the writing was the saying for her. She does not double-dip on the rule."

    "He wants to say something to her about the board."

    "He does not."

    "He has learned the lesson of s06. The lesson is that the board is not the scene. The board is the altar and the altar is in the room for the scene that is about to happen, but the scene is not the altar."

    "He waits."

    # ========== PHASE 4 — THE RULE SHE IS NOT DOING TONIGHT ==========

    "Tessa speaks first."

    t "I want you to do something for me tonight."

    "It is not the voice she has been using with him for the first half of Act IV. It is not the medic voice and it is not the board voice and it is not the corridor-stop voice. It is a voice he has not heard out of her yet in this act. It is the voice she has been keeping for a scene she has been deciding whether to have."

    a "Tell me."

    "A beat. She turns. She faces him for the first time tonight. Her face is not composed in the chosen way from s06. It is not uncomposed, either. It is the face of a woman who has put something down and has not picked up what comes next yet."

    t "I want you to not bring me your wounds tonight."

    "He does not answer right away."

    "He is reading the sentence. He is reading the sentence the way he reads a Selene briefing — front to back, once, and then back to front, once, to see what the sentence means when you run it in the other direction."

    "Front to back: do not bring me your wounds tonight."

    "Back to front: tonight. Wounds. Me. Bring. Not."

    "Both directions say the same thing."

    athought "She is asking me not to be the one in the room who is being tended to."

    athought "Three scenes in a row I have been the one in the room who has been tended to. S05a was her overruling me about rest. S12 was her hand on my sternum. S06 was her adding KESA MARIN and JOREN HALE silently on the board while I watched. I have been the one Tessa has been holding for half of this act."

    athought "She is not asking me to hold her back by rote. That is not the sentence. The sentence is more specific than that."

    athought "She does not want me to bring her my wounds. She is asking for a room where the traffic is not running in its established direction."

    a "Tell me what you mean."

    t "I have spent this act counting."

    t "I have added names to the dead column and I have transferred names up to the living column and I have watched Davel Ostra move from one side of the board to the other in the span of nine hours, and I did not say any of them aloud, because I am in the silent phase of the ritual, and the silent phase is working, and I am not complaining about the silent phase."

    t "But I have spent this act counting."

    t "I would like, for one hour, to be counted by someone else."

    # ========== PHASE 5 — THE SPECIFICATION ==========

    "He does not move."

    "He is letting the sentence exist in the room for as many beats as it needs."

    a "Tell me what that means."

    "She is very still. Her thumb is at her palm again — the gesture from s06, the gesture of a woman holding a rule in her head. Tonight the rule is different. The rule tonight is one she is inventing in front of him."

    t "It means do not check my pulse."

    t "It means look at me like I am not a medic."

    t "It means let me be not-useful."

    "The third sentence is the one she has been deciding whether to say."

    "She says it and the saying is the scene's hinge."

    tthought "I have never said that sentence out loud to anyone. I have said the first two. I have said versions of the first two to exactly one person in my life and that person was my mother and I was fourteen. I have never said the third to anyone."

    tthought "The third is the one I have been afraid to say because saying it would require me to believe it applied to me. I have been the useful one in every room for twenty-three years. I do not know who I am when I am not being useful. The not knowing is the reason I am saying it tonight — because I am tired of knowing who I am only inside the shape of what I am doing for somebody else."

    tthought "He is not going to laugh. He is not going to try to fix this by telling me I am not just my usefulness. He is going to do exactly what I am asking him to do, which is the hardest version of it, and I trust him to do it because I have watched him learn how to sit inside a room this act and not rearrange it."

    athought "Not-useful."

    athought "That is Noelle's word from three nights ago in the interlude I saw on Tessa's datapad when Tessa was at the supply cache. Noelle used it about herself and then put the datapad down and went to the chapel. I did not see Noelle use it — Tessa did. Tessa saw Noelle's sentence and is repeating it on herself tonight. They are not coordinating. They are arriving at the same door from different corridors."

    athought "That is what this act has been. Not a choir. A relay."

    a "I can do that."

    t "I need you to be sure."

    a "I am sure."

    t "I need you to be sure in a way that is not you saying yes because I asked. I need you to be sure in the way that makes the yes a yes you chose."

    "He closes his eyes for a beat. When he opens them, he is looking at her and only at her."

    a "Tessa. I am sure. The board is still there. The rule is still running. I am not going to spend the next hour pretending you are not the woman who counts. I am going to spend the next hour not asking you to count anything."

    a "That is the version of yes I have."

    t "That is the version I was asking for."

    # ========== PHASE 6 — THE DECLASSIFYING ==========

    "She does not step toward him yet."

    "She reaches up to her own shoulders. Her hands find the front closures of her medic jacket. The jacket is the Phoenix field-medic grey, the one with the red cross sewn over the left breast pocket, the one she has been wearing every time he has seen her for the last seventeen days. She is not used to taking it off in front of anyone who is not also a medic. She is not taking it off for the reason a woman takes off a jacket in the first scene of an intimate beat. She is taking it off because the jacket is the uniform, and the uniform is the thing she is putting down."

    "The first closure."

    "The second."

    "The third."

    "She slides the jacket off her shoulders. Her undershirt is beneath it — a plain grey crew neck, soft, civilian, old. The crew neck is the thing under the uniform. It is the thing that has been under the uniform for seventeen days."

    "She folds the jacket."

    "The folding takes three movements. She does them the way she does everything — with attention. Sleeve in. Sleeve in. Length in half. The fold is a folded rectangle of grey on her palm."

    "She walks two steps to the treatment bench and sets the jacket on the bench."

    "Not on the floor."

    "The bench."

    "The same bench from a3_s13. The same bench from a4_s05a."

    athought "She is putting the uniform on the bench because the bench is where she keeps the uniform when the uniform is not doing work. She is telling me what the bench is for tonight and she is telling me by not narrating it."

    athought "This is not disrobing. This is declassifying."

    "She straightens up. Her hands are empty. She turns back to him."

    "The jacket is on the bench. Her shoulders are in the crew neck. The clip lamp on the board is still on. The vigil candle in the corner of the room is still on. She is standing in a medbay she runs, in a base she keeps running, and for the next however long this lasts, she is not the medic in the room."

    "She is a woman in a medbay in a crew neck and the crew neck is old and she is thirty-one years old and her father did not come back from a winter twenty-four years ago and she has been counting since."

    "She is not counting right now."

    "He can see her not counting."

    # ========== PHASE 7 — THE FIRST TOUCH ==========

    "He moves first."

    "Not toward her whole body — toward the one place that is already the right place. His right hand finds her left elbow. Not the wrist, not the shoulder. The elbow. The place a friend holds a friend who is standing at a funeral and does not know what to do with their own arms."

    "The touch is not medical. He is very deliberate about it — he is not checking the pulse at the brachial. He is not feeling for a tremor. He is holding an elbow the way you hold an elbow when you love the person the elbow is attached to and you want them to know their elbow is safe inside your hand for the next minute."

    "It is also not sensual. Not yet. The scene has not done sensual yet and the scene is not going to rush to sensual because the scene is doing something harder than sensual first."

    "It is the grief-hand."

    "She closes her eyes."

    tthought "He knew where to start."

    tthought "He started at the elbow. I was not sure he was going to know where to start and he started at the elbow. The elbow is the place my mother used to hold me at funerals when I was small and did not know what to do with my arms. I never told him that. He did not learn it from me. He learned it from some other funeral he was at. He is bringing his funeral-learning into my funeral-learning and the two of them are the same shape of learning."

    tthought "The seventeen days I have been counting and not being counted on are stacking in my chest right now and I can feel the stack moving."

    "Her right hand comes up."

    "It finds his hand where his hand is on her elbow. She does not move his hand. She lays her hand on top of his hand — palm down, her fingers over his knuckles, her thumb at the inside of his wrist but not taking his pulse. Just resting there. The thumb is a thumb tonight. It is not an instrument."

    "They stand in that configuration for a long beat."

    "Then she takes the step."

    "One step forward. Her body comes into his. Her forehead finds the place where his collarbone meets his throat. His right hand is still on her elbow because neither of them have moved their hands. His left arm comes up around her shoulders the way an arm comes around a shoulder when the arm is not deciding to — when the arm has been waiting for a reason to and the reason has finally come."

    "She does not cry."

    "She is not going to cry. Tessa has not cried in front of Aeron in any scene in this act and she is not breaking that tonight. She is doing a thing that is different from crying. She is leaning her weight onto him and the leaning is her letting the count run on someone else's counter for the length of a held minute."

    "He holds her."

    # ========== PHASE 8 — THE CONSENT GATE ==========

    "After the minute, she lifts her head."

    "Not to leave the embrace. To look at him. Her face is very close to his face. Her eyes are on his eyes. The clip lamp on the board is behind her. The candle is behind him. The two light sources put a warm line down the middle of the small space between their mouths."

    t "I am going to ask you something."

    a "Ask."

    t "I am asking you what the next hour of this is."

    t "I have three answers I would accept. I want you to pick the one that is true for you and I want you to pick it knowing that any of the three is the right answer tonight and that I am not going to be disappointed by any of them."

    "She is giving him the frame she would want to be given if she were in his position. Tessa is always a medic. Even tonight. The medic shape of her caretaking is porous enough to include the consent conversation, and the consent conversation is the last medic-thing she is going to do in this scene before she stops doing medic-things."

    "The choices surface in Aeron's head the way her three readings surfaced in s06. She is speaking the structure before she speaks the options. He is catching up to her structure and deciding inside it."

